at I went to the - the church of England, the low church was then - there's the low church and - and occasionally, or very rarely - oh, very rarely at a high church. Now it's crept in you see, in those early days confession, a crucifix and all that was Po
pery. Yes. And - the great majority of people, especially in a town like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}
 which was non-conformist it was - very much opposed to Popery. Processions, incense, and I went to one of these churches - the - Popery church in Luton, St Savaiours, at the same
 time I was going to a - a Seron Hall, that was the - Methodist - Bible class, I get mixed up with the two of them, then I started to - to study up Darwinism, the - got the \{BLANK\}
 and - I didn't understand much about it but gradually was reading - those sort of books - I became an - an agnostic like yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did your mother do all the cleaning in the house herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You never had anyone to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Still we all helped you see, it was customary in those days for the children 
- from young children, for instance the knives in those days was sharpened with brick dust what - and my duty - my duty was to - after I'd done work mind you I was at work each - each night you see and Saturdays and Sundays - so it didn't give me much tim
e apart from my half. I was a half time schooler. Until I was - I left school at the age of twelve, but from eight until twelve I - I was part time. So didn't give me much - time to - to acquire academic qualifications.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you just go in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
I used to go late in the morning and part time in the after - part in the afternoon, leaving off about - half past three, so on. Yes. Start at ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did mother do the mending of the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 My mother was a - quite a qualified - ne
edlewoman - through sheer necessity I suppose. For instance she used to make shirts, she was quite a shirt maker, all hand of course. Pardon? So - she'd be - she made - she made all my clothes - she even made my clothes when I was a milk boy, when I was n
ine, yes. Short trousers and Sander Jackets. But she was wonderful shirt maker and used to earn money making the shirts. Yes. So that was - that was quite an addition you see to the family income.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you remember if father helped mend shoes or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, no, no, he was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did he help around the house with jobs, cleaning or cooking or washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 He would help - yes, he would help, he was quite a good step-father, yes, he was - he's my step-father, I was the only one left you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Oh he was - quite a man about the house. Yes, he was - yes, and - I'm afraid my mother - of course he was forty, she was thirty when he died, but - there must have been a lot of regard because when she came to Luton
 - she - as a young girl in the hat trade - she - she was pushed around quite a bit you see with relatives and - more or less she was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 We were talking about father doing jobs around the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. But of course in those - in those days - in th
ose days - unemployment - was - as would be confirmed in - in - in my friends book, a History of Luton see my step-father - was in the building trade and the building trade was controlled to a large extent upon - the - the engineering trade, those two if 
i
f engineering was rather bad and of course that was - I'm talking now before the advent of the car. See I can remember when there were no cars about at all. In my grandfather's - horse and cart, which I was - been riding around with him - was going along 
a
 country road just outside Luton, and - one of these chunk-chunk cars came up the road, and the horse shied and - jumped over the - short hedge into the field, so was half in the field and half in the ditch you see. That was quite customary. You could wal
k up the centre of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose} at that time - any old time of the day without being interfered with at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You were telling me about your mother being pushed around from relation to relation a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And her regard for your father, do you know how they met?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
They met through - they met through the - my father being associated in the hat trade, and the people that she was living with - as a young girl - were - going to this particular - warehouse, run by a man named Osborn, who became even
tually the mayor, and - she met him in that way. Well then she became - she was - working at the time - for Carruthers. Carruthers of - quite a big factory in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}
, and so they sort of teamed up between the - the three factories, that's how it came about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And when he died she was very upset was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes, right - right 'til the time when she - when she died I can remember - she said - my Al's - Albert, his name was Albert, she used to call him Al, so I was always a favourite boy somehow - if I - 
that she - always remembered - her husband by - when she saw me. I was belonging to him. Nevertheless she was - she - she had a great love for - my step-father. I did, I never - I never made any difference between - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You never resented him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, never resented. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I expect he was a nice man then was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How did you feel about your step-brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well just my brothers and sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You didn't make any difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No. Not - not the slightest, rather queer, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That was good wasn't it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you remember at all your father helping to dress and undress you and put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. I can remember my own father - my own father - customary to kiss children, I remember one
 particular day he went off to work, and - I'm I remember, I must have been about - I must have then been about four years of age, I can distinctly remember the - the - the part of the road where I managed to run down and catch him up and he'd forgotten t
o
 kiss me. And it must have been at least a half mile away. Yes, so - I was - a great deal of affection. I think then in those days that - family life - if you follow, meant a - a great deal - mixing in together, especially Christmas times and so on - one 
-
 is all the the - joys of getting together, there wasn't much money, I remember the - the very - stringent times, when my brother was then alive - helped me tie up our trousers and the bottom and hang 'em on the bed then - pretend to be asleep and mother 
would come in and fill 'em up with bundles of firewood and so on, with - something nice just at the top you see, but deliberately - playing a joke. Those sort of things happened, you made your own enjoyments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You had a lot of fun even if you didn't have a lot of money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have any tasks in the house that you had to do particularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Any what dear? Task -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was it your job to clean shoes or lay the fire or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes, I - I - I used to - my - my - my - p
articular - jobs were - cleaning the - cleaning the - the cutlery - on a board you know, with the brick dust, you - you don't know of that do you? Well of course - they were steel knives or were supposed to have been, and in order to clean them this brick
 dust was bought, it was a very fine powder, and there was a board for the purpose, you sprinkled the brick dust on the board, and then you - you sharpen - you sharpened and cleaned the knives the same time, do you follow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Rubbing them up and down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
That's - rubbed it up - well the same with the fenders - going - coming round the - and even the fire grates, they had to be polished with - black polish. The fenders, the top of the fenders were again steel that came round, see the - the kerb there, th
at would be - a steel top which had to be cleaned with the brick dust. And that brick dust - method of cleaning the steel ware was quite a common thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you like doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you mind doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, well one had to do
 it you see because there was more disci - there was a good deal of discipline, to bring up a family of - four, six, seven or eight children needed - some discipline, and although - one loved one's parents and the parents - returned the love and so on, bu
t
 - there was an occasional clip - so - to bring you up - as a matter of fact although I had a great respect for my mother, she had grim times in - losing those children and her husband, and fighting to - to keep things going, pay the expenses, oftentimes 
g
etting up to her neck in debt - I remember the baker refusing to leave her - the bread, because she was so much in debt, owing to unemployment, and my step-father being unemployed for a long four months. And so those sort of things happened. But - but nev
ertheless - there was that sort of respect and and love - you know, which - it - it - it forced people that - that way didn't it. It brought out the - it brought out the deep feelings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Sometimes its mothers it altogether I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh possibly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 But in your family obviously there was a lot of love.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have to help - you were the youngest in the end weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I was the youngest of that first family. Yes. But meantime - meantime you see my step-father - w
as a live when my two sis - little sisters died-follow? See I - I went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Do you remember your older brothers and sisters helping you at all with things like dressing and doing up your buttons and your shoes and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well when my bro
ther - my brother, 'cos he was the - he was the only one older than me - follow? I was - yes, I - yes, I used to help in many ways - he used to help me with a - with my school - school work too, yes, he helped me even - a - a labour exam was necessary in 
order to leave at the age of twelve. A labour exam. That was like - like university qualification you see. But it at twelve, otherwise you - you - you had to stay until you were thirteen. Follow?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What sort of standard was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? Of educatio
n? Well - I suppose primitive according to present day standards but - we got by reasonably well, for instance - now - my friend there Doctor Downey - is - some years my junior I know but - he had a - an ordinary - school board education, an elementary ed
ucation - and he - he became an apprentice at one of the little firms \{BLANK\}
 served his five year apprentice, but - at the same time he - he qualified for his - equivalent to the - GCE, got his teacher's certificate, he came - BS Bachelor of Science and th
en - PhD, and - those sort of things did happen through - sheer force of personality somehow. Yes. But I - I wouldn't have - we could - we could read and write and I'd got some idea of geography and - a little bit - and a little small knowledge with gramm
a
r, not much, but by - carrying on as so many other boys did - children - joining the - the - there's - in those days there was the - the Friends Adults. The Friends Adult Movement was of course fostered as you know by the Quakers, and there were Friends A
d
ult Schools all over the country, the idea was - at the back of it, the Quakers wanted to help - people to learn to read and write in order to read the Bible. That was - that was the - original idea. But those schools gradually - there's not one left in L
u
ton, I became president of the Central Adult School - and was - president for a number of years, and I also belonged to another - adult school at the same time. But they became debating societies. Mostly agnostics. Yes. It's rather queer. But those - earl
y schools, they competed with the School Board and the Church schools in those very early days. So you managed to get some knowledge if you - if you want to, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Going back to when you were small do you remember having to go to bed at a particular time, was your mother strict about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Well - in the later years you see, when - when I was on - I'm now talking - when I was - now when I was - eleven, I became - I became - an errand boy for a chemist, the firm still exists in Luton. A
nd - my - time for leaving off was nine at night. Saturday night ten. Follow? That was not unusual, in the - in the hat trade used to - see, in - in the hat trade, there's the history of it in here, very often times people - young people worked all night,
 until it was forced by law the Shaftesbury - Act, prevented them from working, girls, not boys - not men, but girls, women - but - up until - not nearly in my - my age - boys could work all sorts of hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 When you finally went to bed did you put yourself to bed or did mother help when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh no, I put myself to bed, oh yes. We all did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And you shared the bedroom?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I shared the bedroom with my brother. In the early days I shared - there were four of us in one room see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 One bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No. But oftentimes the - the history there, you'll find lots of times there's been five in a bed. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You didn't have a bathroom obviously but did you have a bath occasionally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes, there was this - this method of a - of
 the large bath which we used for washing purposes too, is - well you've seen them - no, perhaps you haven't. No - you're too young. A - a - just a - a - a sort of a steel - iron - there be what we - what is called spelter, a mixture of iron and steel, an
d - quite a sizeable bath, which quite customary - in the back kitchen, do you follow, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How did you heat the water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? Well heated it - on the fire you see. On the - big boilers. The fire then was a coal fire, but built right up it was 
- with the ovens - the oven one side and another sort of container the other - for other purposes, but - the - well the - the coal fire had to heat the oven, for cooking purposes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How often did you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Once a week. Somewhere about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you all have it the same night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
No. No, that was spread over - some period you follow? The younger children had - I remember my mother - washing the little girls, those that died - quite frequently, I suppose everybody - body would have don
e that but I mean the - the - the bath was quite good for young children, and - and - youngsters up to the age of - seven or eight you know. I mean I can remember - pop as we used to call him, having his - weekly - wash down and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That was your step-father was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes. But nearly all the houses - well of course as you perhaps know, you - the houses - there must be any amount I know exist round where you lived - they were just the two up and two down weren't they, with the outside toilet up t
he - end of the garden and so on. Quite customary.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have clean clothes after you had a bath do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? Yes, my mother was rather fas - I think most women were - but, now I - I - you see, this washing - was quite a - quite a
 terrific business, because they were large families. I mean - invariably meant - two or three washed a week, or - if there was a long long line, you did - the - the - did the job, but I remember on one occasion things were so awful - that - my mother - h
u
ng her washing out one evening - must have been - in the autumn time when the darkness would come on, and when she went out to fetch them in they were all gone. So she went - in the next street where - we had been friendly, up to that time, with a - a - a
 
man named Detective Chamberlain, and - he said, is there any - is there any mark that you can remember on any of these clothes? She said, yes. She says, there's a scissor's rust mark - on a table cloth. Well he immed - immediately went down to the pawn sh
o
p - there were the clothes. Chasing - chasing the - tracing where - where the - the clothes came from, the particular person who'd pawned them, it was the young girl next door, aged fourteen. And she had seven days hard labour. Yes. My mother - my mother 
was - frantic about it. Because - she wouldn't have - she wouldn't have proceeded if she'd known - 'cos - they were even worse off than we were I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Punishment was hard wasn't it in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Seven days hard labour, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Can we talk a bit about meals, where did you eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
In the - in the sort of middle - in the middle room which was - which we - we would say was the dining room. That was the back - back room, the front room was the - the - the parlour and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you ever eat in the parlour, special meals or tea or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
No, well it's just - one - it was living up with the Jones's, there had to be a parlour somehow. And if there wasn't any - any furniture in the parlour well the - the blind was kept closed you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You had a parlour but no furniture in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And your mother cooked on this coal oven thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, but you see - now - I can remember - I can remember very well lots of times going down to the butchers - the che
apest butcher in the town which was in the main street, and buying two penny \endash 
 two pennyworth of pieces, that's beef, two pennyworth of pieces, that's the odd pieces knocked off here and there, you follow, and a pennyworth of suet, that was three pence, and that made a pudding for the lot of us. Then again -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Your mother was a good cook was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I beg your pardon? Oh yes, but of course that was - that was a must you see, any amount of people did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What did you have for breakfast, do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Well - butter of course was - no, butter wasn't - butter wasn't used by - the ordinary - working class people. It was dripping, see, largely dripping. Lard wasn't known much but there - there was lard because that was - lard from the - from
 the - various cooking - there wasn't lard - lard as we know now. But the - the dripping was - bought quite cheaply. Butter then was - I - remember - selling butter as a milk boy - a shilling - shilling a pound, shilling a pound, that's right, yes. Shilli
ng a pound, yes, but of course milk was tuppence a - tuppence a pint follow. And beer was tuppence a pint.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You'd have bread and dripping for breakfast would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Bread and dripping, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Anything else, anything to drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well there was - there was - there was tea, you bought the tea at four pence ha'penny \endash 
 four pence ha'penny, plus - some sort of token for a present when you got enough tokens. There's - a sixpenny ha'penny bazaar which sold tea and you had a - a present at the same tim
e. And of course the penny bazaar then was in operation, the penny bazaar which was - the - origin I suppose of Woolworth\rquote s and those sort of people. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So you didn't drink tea very much because it was quite expensive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What about midday, what would you have had midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Midday, well there wouldn't be - there wouldn't be meat, you'd only have the - meat would only happen about once a week, meat was beyond you follow? It would be bread and - dripping and so on, there might be occasi
onal - little - puddings. Puddings - mothers would concoct puddings up with very little cost and - make them quite nutritious. Vegetables - vegetables were - were cheap you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So you had vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have a stew at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
There was - vegetables. There was - a mixture of vegetables, you could - potatoes and the rest, cabbages and what have you, vegetables, quite - quite reasonable in - cost.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You used to come home from school for that did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Come home from school at lunch time, yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have tea in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 When we come over from - from school, there'd be - there'd be the bread and dripping and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was there anything else after that, any supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I remember that 
we used to have - there was a - a - there was some sort of a four - four meal day. Yes. There would be a supper, I remember coming home late at night and having - having a meal. Of a sort. Because fish and chip you could get a - you could get fish and chi
ps for three ha'pence, a penny piece of fish and - and a ha - ha'penny worth of chips, or a ha'penny piece of fish. A penny would - in those days would - buy a supper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That was quite good value wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So you'd have that when you came in at nine o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
On - on special occasions, I didn't get those - that very often. No. But - but - we - used to have it - on the odd occasion, oftentimes Saturday evening. That was pay day you follow. Of course you see the step-father the
n would be earning about twenty-two shillings a week. I remember on one occasion - on one - winter time when things was - tough - there was nothing in the building trade, and he managed to get - a temporary job with the local - railway - company at that t
i
me, and - he worked from six at night until six in the morning and six days a week for sixteen shillings. That's for twelve - that's sixty hours a week. But I worked you see until I retired a - a few years ago, I - I worked sixty hours a week right throug
h my working life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did mother make her own bread do you remember or jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, my mother - odd occasions made her own bread but - they didn't seem to have much - time for making bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did she make jam or pickles or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Oh yes, they used to make their own jams. Yes. Blackberry jam. Was quite a - that's quite a seasonable - quite - quite a - a seasonable thing to do, making jam from blackberries, we used to go blackberrying, almost all - everybody went blackberrying round
 - round the district.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That's was free wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did she bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, I don't remember her - her bottling. Pardon? She might have done but - it was - mostly - for the immediate - needs, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did father make any beer or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 He liked a drink did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
He drank - yes, he - he drank in his - I'm afraid that's another point you see that - that oftentimes spoilt - you see in his early days my step-father did lik
e his drink and it was my mother's determination to cure him which she did. Gradually. She was that forceful nature. It needed - sometimes a - a - a friendly biff. But - but my - my - my own father was more or less a teetotaler, it's rather queer. But dru
nkenness then was very rife. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And of course it went away with the money didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes, and - and I mean - it was customary those days for - in the hat trade - for men to have Monday off to get over Sunday's drunkenness. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you remember if they kept any - did they have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did they grow any vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes - used to grow - oh yes - used to grow and - and of course my step-father he bought - eventually he bought - forty poles of - land nearby for vegetable growing. Sixteen shillings a pole. You can imagine what it'd be worth today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have any livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Now - it's rather queer that - my mother and - my step-father very fond - and - yes, they were very fond of chickens, a
nd in keeping rabbits. Unfortunately they used to make - make such a - favourites of the rabbits, you see, and eventually when they'd be killed well we couldn't eat them. They used to have a name like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Alice{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and so on, Tom. But the chickens I can - I can re
member - oh right the way through my step-father's life - with - with us that he would have his - this chicken - hen house as they used to call them, with about six or seven - fowls and lay - laying the eggs you see. Chickens.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So that supplemented things didn't it? Your own father didn't keep anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes. I remember an ornamental garden he did a wonderful ornamental garden with - these fancy - these fancy - fences, and - oh yes, I can remember a hen house at the top - quite an attract
ive place, going back in my memories, yes, yes, he had fowls too. I suppose it must have been - it must have been the customary thing to have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 It helped out didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How many times a week would you think you ate meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How many what duck?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh not more than - twice, no. Oftentimes only once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was there much poaching went on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, as a matter of fact, it's rather - my father's brother, there were three brothers, Alber
t - Reuben, one named after who was a manufacturer of hats and in quite a nice way of business, and - Eli, who was a plasterer, but his one fun in life was poaching. And he - I think - I think he still holds the she used to go round - if there did happen 
to be any odd pieces left on other peoples plates - that she had them. She always used to clear the plates up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were you allowed to talk during meals when you were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Could you talk while you were sitting at the table or did you have to be quiet during a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
As a child you mean? Yes, we could talk. Yes, my mother was - quite - reasonable with regard to - the - conduct - mind - mind you, she - she was pretty stern like they had to be. Follow? But - she was - she was very - friendly to us all, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have to eat everything up or could you leave something if you didn't like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 We'd eat everything up. You see - you see, food wasn't too plentiful. For instance, as a - as a milk boy - as a milk boy -
 coming in - in the winter time - off the round - sometimes I remember distinctly - the snowy morning - when I looked forward to - to getting in the home, having a - what was then a pepper and salt mess, you wouldn't know would you about - a pepper and sa
lt mess was simply hot water, pepper and salt with - broken up bread - a hot - hot meal, sometimes with lard or a little drop of - of - dripping, melted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was that nice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 It was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you ever have second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, we didn't - w
e didn't go short, we didn't go short of food, but the food you see was - lacking in the - nutrition, you see, my two young - my two sisters died as a result of malnutrition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How about table manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well we had to - we had to conform to - a str
ict - method of table manners. Yes. I think that was more or less general. I wouldn't say they were - ultra-aristocratic with regard to the techniques but still they - they conformed. Yes. I should think that would be general. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were you allowed ever to bring a book to the table or a toy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Record, according to my - historical - friend, he still holds the record around here for poach - a hundred and twelve convictions - for poaching. In those days - in those days - a man couldn't be arrested on
 Sunday for poaching. And he was particularly good with his - he could run. He was very good - he - he was quite a good runner, and - he could - if necessary of a Saturday night, it was always night time poaching in the nearby - what was called Kidney Wic
k
 belonging to the - the - the big estate, which of course - now belongs to the Werns, but these huge woods were just the ideal for spots for poaching. My uncle - used to supply - or - like - used to - always be able to get rid of his - his - partridges an
d whatever they were to a well known - shop in Chapel Street, and - I can quite remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did any of them come your way ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? I don't - well my - that's rather funny, my father got a - a - an aptitude for poaching, but not - not that
 sort of poaching. I remember - my mother telling me that when - when he - well, hadn't been married very long and - a friend of his used to - go around to the - public houses for some reason or other with a card. And on this particular night - the - his 
f
riend who was driving the cart, horse and cart, told my father that his - wife was - ill, or she was recovering - and she liked chicken, so - and I know the pub - still know the pub at Barton where it happened, that while the - this friend was delivering 
something into the pub my father - went down to the back - into the - henhouse and just chose a very nice chicken and - brought it home and that was that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you remember at mealtimes seeing that your mother was having less so that you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
In the early days - yes, I can remember - before, of course this go - this goes back to - to the early days before she was married the second time, the - the - the very tragic days between - the years - of my - years of five and so on up to about ei
ght or nine. That - this - this food business oftentimes I can - well remember - her having - little herself. Because, well there wasn't enough food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So she gave it to you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you know if father had bigger helpings than anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
My step-father? No. No. We - we went on - I - I can remember my sister who died in May though it's rather queer, she was the - she was the youngest sister, before my - last brother came along, she was the youngest, and she - A - a - toys? We 
did read, my mother - rather - strange but my mother was quite a - an educated woman considering the - the circumstances which she came about you see, she was brought up by - her grandmother who lived at Bedmond - in Hertfordshire, and she was - I believe
 
I told you before, she was the local - midwife and - a witch doctor and all the rest of it but she also must have had some sort of - education, which - she handed on to her children and to her - her grandchild, my mother. So my mother was quite a reader. 
Rather queer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And she encouraged you to read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
She - she used to read - all sorts of - books, there was no sort of local library at the time - before the time of - libraries, but there were certain books - similar to the Woman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 s Own - and - in - 
in those - in those early days and I remember she used to manage to take - one book, and I used to comb her hair in the afternoon, her long hair, which - used to keep her going sometimes just for little - laps in between the making of the hats, sewing of 
the hats or sometimes when she was sewing the hats I'd brush her hair, which she seemed to enjoy, or - or she - she'd be reading the book at the Sun - on the Sunday - in the Sunday after - afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 She had long hair did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Oh yes, that w
as customary, mind - mind you the long hair was then - plaited up you see, curled up in to a - a bun. And of course the - the bonnet then was quite prevalent - not the big hat, it was the little bonnet. I remember when - I remember as a small child - seei
ng her in her - widows weeds, the little - long frock you see and - the - the veil came - coming - coming down from the bonnet. After - after the funeral, some time. It was customary at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did I ask you if you went to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I - I - did I go to the funeral? No, I was only - I was only five you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And you weren't taken?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you all have to stay at the table 'til everyone had finished the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You could get down when you'd finished?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well
 - you see, I - for - in the first place I was at work you see as a boy, in - in the young - in young days - we used to have to get around the house doing certain jobs and so on. As small children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have your own places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Always sat in the same place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes, same - same places, yes. And the same with the beds you see. And naturally there were about two - two or sometimes - there has been three in a bed but two - normally, two in a bed I should say lots o
f families - lots of families as I said before would be - an average of about six children. Lots of families of course ten, one near us - was a family of twenty-three. Twenty-three, yes. Twenty-three children, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 All the same generation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, same mother, same father, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How did they live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were they poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Mind - mind you the - the man was - the man was a - sort of builder, he was - a little bit more - prosperous with regard to the average type of - income. But - ne
vertheless the children, so far as I remember, were - graded right the way up but I think they were almost all of them alive. Yes. And he was a very tall of about six foot three - so far as I - remember, and - the woman was just about - about five foot od
d, just a little bit - it was rather queer. Quite strange.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What sort of house did they live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? They lived - ah the house was a little larger than ours. I believe it was a four bed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 roomed house. I - yes, I think it was a four bed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 roo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 med house so far as I can remem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
ber, it was a longer back - a - the building at the back was more - commodious somehow. Either by length or width. Still - but ten children were - weren't abnormal. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Who served the meal, did mother serve the meal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did father carve? Did you ever have a joint?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, father - 'cos I'm now - my own father I don't remember quite well - see I was five when he died, my own father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How about your step-father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Step-father, no, he didn't - a
lthough he - he came from a - a market gardener family - who would be - well the family would be versed in that sort of thing, poultry and what have you, no, he didn't do anything like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Mother did it all did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Yes. Well you see 
she would have to - cater - and she would know precisely what amount of this, that and the other each child would need, so - but the - the puddings and all that, although that type of food - she catered for. But as the years got on - see - with the second
 
family - prosperity came into it more because my - my step-sisters, my half-sisters I should say, were earning reasonable money in the hat trade but - that was before the first world war, but - later on then my family - my family happened you see last cen
tury.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So things got a bit easier for her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That was - that was more - more grim of course, conditions were grim.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did - sorry? Yes, oh yes. Yes, rather, she was rather a - a friendly sort of person. Jocular. Very. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was she affectionate towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 She showed her affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How about father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. Both of them. The step-father and my own father, my own father was - a very - friendly man. But of cou
rse - he died as - as you know, when - quite early.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did they expect you to behave in a certain way towards them? Were you expected to be respectful?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well - yes, I think there was a mutual respect in those days from children to the parents, mind
 you I think - generally speaking parents had to be more strict, naturally in order -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
To control a bigger family. You follow? It was - oftentimes - a clip at the side of the ear is - which was - quite an accepted thing wasn't it mother? My 
wife's mother, now she was a very gentle person, my wife's mother - a - a different person altogether, my mother was - strict - she had to be. In order to keep us - alive as best she could in those very very early days, it - it - it - it was a grim time. 
I mean like any amount of people will - simply went into the work house automatically. The work house was quite a usual thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 Di}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 d you remember people going into it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes, I remember - I - I - oh yes, quite a number. The work house building is still at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton
{\*\xmlclose} but it's used now as a - as an old peoples infirmary - been extended and - it's now for people - like for instance I had a sister die - die in it you see in May.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you ever go in it when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Not me, no, but I had - one sister die in the - the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bute
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Hospital{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, at the age of eighty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you remember what it was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bute{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Hospital{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was a kind of small hospital - and kept up by - voluntary - contributions, and - the - there was a means test, for instance
, my mother - my mother had to pay a half a crown a week for my little sister who was in hospital, dying from - from - heart disease. I broke my arm at school in the playground - my mother had to pay - she had to find somehow five shillings - to pay the d
octor's fee before he set my arm, or some - the - similar circumstances, and at the same time she was paying half a crown a week - my sister being in the hospital you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What was it like in there, do you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh quite good. Quite a small hospital, it was quite a good hospital. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You used to go and see her did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did your parents expect you to behave towards each other, your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes, they - I think - there was in those days a friendly atm
osphere with - between - I remember going to the - the nearby church. 'Course church activities in those days catered for the enjoyment - before - before the moving pictures - before there was anything like moving pictures - the churches and the non-confo
r
mist places catered a lot for the enjoyments of young people. The churches had their - the social activities, later on whist drives and - they learned to dance and so on, not so at the chapel, they were more - they - they were a Band of Hope meetings, the
 temperance meetings, those sort of activit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 ie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
s with regard to the non - non-conformist church but - chapels but with regard to the churches, there were - games of different - sorts, there was - calecinics - evenings. We even ran a - we even ran our church ran a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 - a nigger troupe, or a minstre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
l troupe. Now the two main minstrel troupes in the country were - Moore and Burgess Minstrels and the Mohawk, the Mohawk Minstrels were similar to the Black and White Minstrels. Well any amount of the churches in the cou
ntry had their little nigger troupes, see, and I belonged to a nigger - this nigger troupe, as a matter of fact - I used to play eventually - you see, in a nigger troupe they have little chorus boys, about eight of us and - and then there were - eight - m
en who sang and then there were - corner men, three each side, corner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  men playing tambourines, banjo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
s, and - bones you see. And these are - now these are - these are - these are in here - my brother was a - a corner man, when I was a small - when I was a yo
ung boy in the - in the chorus I wanted to become eventually a corner man, you follow, they were the stars at the time you see, and - they played the bones you see. See? See? And I - I used to - well I used to play four in each hand. Well - they - they're
 all gone apart from those two you see. Now they were the nigger troupe, the Minstrel bones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 They're just wood aren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. Very hard wood. And - and as - see we used to go round the villages of the little - village halls, the schools and
 out - and - our - and - give concerts you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That must have been fun?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes. But all those sort of activities made something. You see during the year the pictures - come - used to come once a year, they were huge - magic lantern - entertainment
s, just sta - stationary static pictures, huge pictures but there'd be a series of them describing a play or something. Well then on Sundays there were magic lantern - lectures - the non-conformist used to have them - describing the - the drink question. 
O
f course the Salvation Army was born about the time of - my - my mother's - being as my mother died at - 1866 - and the - the Salvation Army - emerged with General Booth - these - these young - these girls, becoming the - Salvation Army girls, and the bon
n
et the - the - the Salvation Army bonnet was then the - the crash helmet. I - I blocked the last one last year - of the Salvation Army bonnet you see, they're going out now, 'cos they now cost nine - nine and a half to ten guineas each. And - now they - f
elt hats - replacing the bonnet, at about a quarter of the price, you follow, so the firm that I - my friend in - nearby, he was the only manufacturer making the Salvation Army bonnet, and at long last he's given up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Why do you say it was a crash helmet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Well I'll tell you why, because - the - the gin drinking at that time - was very cheap you see, and the bottle the men used to - the drunken men used to hit the girls on the - biff 'em you see. Oh yes. So right the way through - and even now - th
ose - Salvation Army bonnets had to be absolutely hard, and made from Chinese plait, sewn together, and - I've got two or three in the local museum, and then they were stiffened very very hard - and - go on the top of the heads, that - just over the crown
 
of the heads so that - they - it - it would stop them being - oftentimes knocked unconscious. So that's the origin of the Salvation Army bonnet. But you see, they - they were the activities then that you made - children have all sorts of games. There wasn
'
t this you see. Those days - you had your fun at Christmas time in all sorts of ways, various games - all sorts of games, to keep - keep the - the family going, and they were really happy times at Christmas although there wasn't much money. To - to get to
g
ether enough money to - to buy - the - the raisins and what have you for the Christmas pudding - and so on, needed - getting together a few - shillings over a matter of weeks. Because you see - in those days there was no payment for holidays, which meant 
to say that - if - if the people didn't work Christmas Day and Boxing Day they had no money. So oftentimes a - a holiday was - well, quite a nuisance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 A day without pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did your parents have ambitions for you, did they want you to grow up to be particular sorts of people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Well, no, you see, I - it - I'm afraid, as I told you, that I passed the la - labour exam, you had to qualify those days to - to leave school, not some - far - further education, in the main. And o
f course, it's rather queer, but the - quite - quite properous manufacturers in Luton - hat manufacturers and worth quite a lot of money, still sent their children - to the - what was then schooled the - the - the Board school or the - Church of England s
chool, or the non-conformist school. Very few sent them to a public school, lots of them could have - could have afforded too. I mean there was the public school at - at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. The Harper Trust Schools. Harper Trust of course was to provide education with - hard up parents you see for the children. But - but it gradually developed that like lots of the other public schools from that source.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was your mother strict about things like swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, oh yes, there was - there was discipline - there w
as discipline with regard to that. Yes. I'll tell you - I'll tell you why I should think, because - almost all children went to some sort of Sunday school, very few - children - lapsed with regard to Sunday school. For one reason, that it meant that the c
h
ildren did go somewhere, follow? Again, that the Sunday schools did provide for lots of different - activities to help children. There was the Sunday school treat which happened once a year. Long - long since that has belong - is forgotten isn't it. Did y
o
u ever go to a Sunday School treat? That's rather queer. Once a year - the children - went to somewhere, now - I went - one - I went - to - about five different churches or chapels - over a matter of seven or eight years, in my very young days, and - the 
meanest one of the lot had a school treat which just meant walking the whole school - walking up to a nearby park which is just over the top of the hill there, but you see the - and that cost about - that - that was about four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence, for the tea. But most -
 most schools went out of the town, or - either in the very early days before the advent of the coach, they went in what was then wagonettes - or brakes, that was pulled by horse you see and there might be three or four wagonettes according to the size of
 
the Sunday school, take the children out. Well they'd go perhaps ten miles away to some some park, or some - aristocratic - ground or something of that sort, from Luton here it used to be - it used to be Hatfield, which of course - is a - a very famous pl
ace - nearby here, or Bicket Woods, there's another place they used to go to, either by train - a little later on, or in the early days by the - the brake or the wag - the wag - the wagonette. And that would cost about seven}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence or eight}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence, each child
. But that was looked forward to. From one year to - to another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What did you do when you got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh there were games in the park, there was a - there was a tea and so on. For instance, when - the Diamond Jubilee happened, Queen 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}, 1897, I remember - all the schools at that time include - I was then eight - we went to the local park, which was then - before the Werners, one time the Mar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 quis of Bute - well the Marqui}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 s of Bute used to be at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}. The Marques of Torns, near - nea}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 rby as you know, and the Marque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 s of - of - the - the Ma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 rque}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 s of - where you live, all - the offspring - of the Charles 11 and his various lady friends you see. Which you know of of course. But that - the Luton Hooe was quite a - quite a place to go to, but you see 
- that - that - Queen {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s Diamond Jubilee, the schools had to walk there. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How far was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 About two to three miles, some about three and a half miles I should think, we had to walk - in procession. And then when we got there we h
ad a mug of tea and a bun. See? Then eventually we came home. But children look forward to that, well now you can understand what children think about that sort of thing today wouldn't you, but it was something. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I should think it would be nice in the wagonettes going off for the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Oh it's quire fun because there was all trimmed up in various ways and then there was no - no - no great expense but it was always something there you see. And the - the Sunday - school authorities - it was - qu
ite an endeavour on the part of them to provide something for the children on that occasion. There was little Christmas parties and so on too. Oh yes, I - I think that helped to keep children - disciplined. At home too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 When you were punished did you just get a clip round the ear or was there anything worse than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, no, that was - just a - just suddenly and - but anyway - you didn't - you - you didn't misbehave very often. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Obviously you got more guidance from your mother when s
he was a widow, but did your father or step-father have any influence on you do you think or was your mother the biggest influence?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 My mother had an influence on me until I was pretty well married. Yes. I wouldn't have - mind you it was in a kindly w
ay but - somehow - my mother - really dominated right the way through, right the way through her life. Yes she is -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 She was a very strong woman was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well she had to be I suppose.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What about birthdays, you tell me that Christmas was quite fun, did you make anything of birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, there was a little birthday - there was not much - there was not much with regard to - refreshments, other than the usual, but - }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 my mother would somehow con}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 trive something. And Christmas -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Would you have had a present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? Might have had a minute present, I don't remember - I don't remember a birthday present. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you ever play any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, it's rather queer because you see - now it's - well - t
wo cars and a - and a bathing pool outside living up with Jones's I suppose but in those days - later on - later on - it was a piano. Yes. Piano and - and lessons - afterwards seeing - as we got - as we got on my step-father - and trade - my step-father -
 
and his children, or my - not my half - brothers and sisters, they were out at work, before the first world war, and - the piano was bought, and music lessons happened with my two sisters. And I borrowed the books and I learned from them, their tuition. B
ut that was the sort of general thing, a piano.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you have musical evenings at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Oh yes, we used to have - used to have real fun, especially at Christmas time. Oh yes, Christmas time was a - we used to - fill the house - house out with - wi
th our little relatives, and my - my mother used to do all sorts of grim jokes and - so on, and - my two sisters could play the piano, I could do a - I could play - after a style, and I had a brother-in-law who could play so we used to have real fun. At C
hristmas time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. And I think that was general. They were family parties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And you played games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, all sorts of games, yes, right - right - right in the - early in the war and - I think it was a recognised thing those 
days to - get the females to bed and then the makes carry on playing nap and so on you see 'til about four or - four in the morning. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You said you didn't go to your father's funeral but did you ever go as a small child attend a funeral of any sort?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes, my two sis - my little sisters afterwards. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Can you describe it to me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Well you see the - I remember - I remember my - the first sister - of course I wasn't very old, about nine or ten - I can remember - the coffin in the - in what was then called the front room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you see her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes, I saw - I saw her in the coffin you see, and I remember my mother showing some - friends - and the - and the pains, 'cos she'd had - heart disease for three years, and - the pain s
omehow had - swollen the - her little chest and it was - it was black with the pain, and it had somehow - it was almost to the - the level of the coffin. Those sort of things were - weren't unusual.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were you frightened seeing her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, yes, I wa
s - I was - rather disturbed about that. But the same thing you see, my other sister, the later one, she died - she died in the - February and my - brother - aged nineteen, twenty, he died within ten months afterwards you see, so I suppose - those - those
 funerals I went to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Would all the family have come, did they all dress in black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. The -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were there many people at the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh no. No. Oh those fune - the funerals in those - early days, they couldn't afford much. You see, t
here was the - the hearse and usually one coach. There wouldn't be two coaches. Not - not the average, be quite a - an economical -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Would they come back to tea afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, a small tea, just a celebration, yes, just a - a little gathering af
terwards. But they would all be - be very sparse and - economical. I'm not - I'm talking now about the - the ordinary working class people. You see in those days well - a man earned about a pound you see, I'm talking about before the first world war, abou
t a pound - pound a week. Well they're a qualified engineer and so on. They was only earning about thirty-five shillings a week after the first world war.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were you taken to visit neighbours, friends and relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. Oh yes. I remember - I 
remember - my wife - wouldn't remember, no, I know she wouldn't, no, I remember the old lady - who was due to go into the work house. Because - she was having a job to keep the rent going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Was she a neighbour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Neighbour, an old lady of nearly se
venty. And we used to help a little bit with food, occasionally, and so on, and we were all very worried about her because she was due to go, then suddenly out of the blue - two gentlemen friends arrived - and they'd come from America, and one of these - 
t
hese men - had been an early - sweetheart of hers in her very young days, had gone to America and settled in Salt Lake City, Utah, or Caterham just outside Utah, and become a Mormon. And they were due to - these two were - two old friends, or the - this o
l
d friend and his - his - pal had - had - had - were going to stay with this Miss Cook for a few weeks, then return home to America. Well - the early days before I used to do - painting and I'd made a - I made a screen, a fire screen and painted flowers on
 the screen, and I remember this old lady saying, when I get married I'd like that screen. Yes, yes, you shall have that screen. Well eventually - she married this old - yes, and she went back to - to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Salt Lake City{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Not only that but this - this old gentle
man was a retired builder, and he was a Mormon, and he got several children, he'd got a big home, a ten roomed home, and he was living by himself he was a widower, well we all thought well he must have got a dozen wives - it wasn't generally known that - 
o
f course - the law marriage had been done away with in America in 1860/1861, but nevertheless - he wrote back and offered my step-father a job as a well sinker, a well sinker, which was quite a job and quite a big prospects, out in Caseville. But - And th
is - this - they went over to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Salt Lake City{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and - my step-father was offered this job, as a - as a well sinker with quite good prospects, and we were all due to go. Family. But - unfortunately the boat that took them over - took Miss Cook and her new husband over - sank, there was}{\rtlch\fcs1 
