adilly Tom, he was the - supposed to be the chief steward. Those two. With all the underlings you see - in my house - that's - in my house is many mansions, do you follow? But that - and of course, in those days, I remember going to a - Toas - to Brisenor
t
on church - this is rather queer. Because - in those days the pews - the pews were allotted according to the - the - the the station of the people - congregation. And the higher up the - the - the people in - in - in stature, they - they got the - the - t
h
e seat nearest the pulpit. Follow? But then there was an - an incorporated society - which - made all seats free, do you know that? Oh well. Well, now - if they - if they had a - a fee from the society that all seats should be free and for - not - hired, 
r
ented and so on, and - anyone went into a seat - they was entitled to that seat. Never mind who - who had been - there before him. And I went into the Brisenorton church once, got up near the pulpit, very early. Queerly enough my - my cousin's husband was
 
one of the wardens, and he hadn't noticed me, one of the church clerks did notice me afterwards. I was sitting in a seat belonging to a very influential family, and - they came and said - came and said - you must - you mustn't sit in this seat. I said - t
h
e - the mark up was the incorporated society they was getting the fee, I said, I'm sitting here, and I stopped there. The people came eventually. Looked at me, they didn't - take any notice. But I felt afterwards rather silly afterwards but there you are.
 
Yet that happened you see with the parish churches. Now of course the non-conformist churches as you know even now - they have their pews, their - their seats and they pay their subs - naturally don't they, that's a different matter altogether but parish 
churches were rather different. But - that's what used to happen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Do you remember your mother being helped out by neighbours or relations when one of you - perhaps when she was ill or father was ill? Do you remember if relations came in or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Well she had - neighbours, oh yes, they were nice neighbours, the neighbours - relations, we didn't have any - relations to - to fall back upon. No, but the - the neighbours, they used to - used to co-operate together quite well, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 If your mother was ill somebody would come in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes. Yes. And even in hard times with regard to - I know that - regard to food, I don't remember as regards my mother, I - I don't suppose she was rather independent - well - we never starved but obviously the fo
od wasn't too - it wasn't - too appetizing you know, it was just the - the best she could do, but - lots of families in different times - you see the pawn shops as I told you - the pawn shops used to be very busy. Especially on Monday in order to - pawn s
o
me things in order to pay the rent. So oftentimes - food was scarce. There's no doubt about it. Remember one - I've a memory - one of the brief times - my mother paid - my mother owed - quite a lot to the - the local baker, and I think the - supply stoppe
d for a time. It was opened up eventually, but those things used to happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did your mother have any particular friends, like a best friend?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. She had a - she had - two or three friends, oh yes. Teamed up together for many many years. And 
- oh yes, until - until she died 1940, she still had - she still had a - one or two old friends. Yes, she did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Would they ever go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. In those early days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Where would they go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Walks and so on and round - or go and visit each others houses and that sort of thing, there wouldn't be much else to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 They used to go to each others houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Would they eat and drink something there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, there'd be a - a little - little - tea together, or afternoon whenever it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
People always say that those years ago you used to make your own amusements, can you remember doing that in your family and other families doing it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you mean - among ourselves? Yes, all sorts of - all sorts of - little g
ames, of course as I - I've told you in those early days, in those early days, if you could manage a piano, you - well you - you could afford one, as the years go on - the piano was - like this you see, which you had to have a piano. That's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And it wasn't just your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Pianos quite a - quite a thing - and - of course there were the - there were the lessons somehow that were got for the - children, I'm talking about the - the - more fluent times after the first world war. But up 'til the firs
t world war - no, I can remember we had a piano, yes, we did, yes, we did in the first world war. When my sisters grew up and they're out at work, you see, when - when children grow up - a family of eight - eventually - there would be two or three out at 
work. You see, children - went out to work when they were - thirteen, fourteen and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So they'd be bringing in a bit of money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 That's right. In the industrial districts. But of course in the rural districts it was rather different. 'Cos there
 wasn't much for children to do. I'll give an instance, in the last world war I know that this doesn't refer now to your - this - this is too late but - the coupons, the - the clothing coupons - which you wouldn't remember would you - would you? Would you
 really? That's surprising. Anyway, it's rather queer because - there was a lot of - there was a lot of fiddling in - clothing coupons. Now a town like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}
 where the women - going out to work, see almost all the women went out to work or did work at home.
 That's one of the reasons why - Luton became an industrial town, to entice manufacturers concerns, engineering concerns to come down to Luton - 'cos the land was cheap and - the - the earnings of the - women in the hat trade could supplement the low earn
i
ngs of the men - men in the engineering trades, that - that's - that's why you'll find that Luton in the - in the - in - in the Library now, same boo, the - Luton Van Company. Well you see, in a war, coupons were regarded as something you see, you knew co
u
pons to get clothes. So - I used to do business with a - a customer - at Nottingham, and he used to supply shops with hats - little village shops, but he used to buy - these clothing coupons from the women in the districts - who it would pay them to sell 
-
 sell the clothing coupons, rather than buy clothes with them you see. So I used to be able to buy - buy - coup - coupons by the hundreds. And then - I used to - a big man in Luton - a big - hood manufacturer, he - he had a nice - sized house near Silso, 
a
nd he wanted carpets and different things of that sort, curtains and - and he used to ring me up, can I have some more - he used to say - call them cigars, can I have another hundred cigars? Used to pay a shilling each for them. So that sort of thing happ
ened. Well the same thing happened you see in the first - before the first world war, those sort of things happened, but - there was certain - sort of things happened in the hat trade and other trades, these - funny little goings on, to get - money.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 D
o you remember your mother thinking of herself as the same social class as your father, was there any difference between them or were they about the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, I don't - no, she came here you see, she was a - she was an orphan - being brought up by he
r grandmother, and she came to Luton - well she had rather a tough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
time, because - she - she came to Luton when she was about fourteen, came into the hat trade - from a rural district, Bedmond, just outside - outside Hemel Hempstead, near Kings Langley - b
ut I told you the - the - the - the chief persons in the district were - the Solly's who owned the village, plus the estates nearby, and all the children had to do as - Lady Solly - said you see, she arranged for them to be maids here and there - there, f
or her friends and so on, and - people had to conform to her wishes. Well - anyway my - great - my great grandmother decided my mother - wasn't to be - made a servant she must come to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}
 in the hat trade. One of mother's relatives was a hat manufacturer in Luton that time so she came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}
. But - this hat manufacturer uncle was rather an intolerant man and he - he treated her as servant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 She was quite an intelligent woman wasn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 So she - beg pardon? Queer enough she - she could read wo
nderfully well as a - a - I don't know how that happened - but my great-grandmother could - she again - I don't know how that happened. 'Cos those days - I go back now to - long before 1866, about 1840 I suppose when my great-grandmother was a girl. So - 
how she managed to read and write I don't know, it was rather - it was rather unique in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did your mother have any views about class do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes, she was very - she was very anti - she was very anti-aristocratic. Aristocracy - 
and of course she was - she was a Republican too, she was - got no time for - mind you - Republicanism in her time, before the first world war was quite rife, people like Joe Chamberlain, Neville Chamberlain's - father was a - was a very prominent Republi
can, at the time of Victoria, after Albert had died, some years afterwards she - she - she became very - she got into her shell sort of do you follow, and - there were any amount of - Republicans at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Your mother was one of them was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Pardon? Yes. Yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Do you remember people saying, oh he's a real gentleman or a real lady? And what would they have meant by that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well they would have meant - they would have meant one of the people like - the - the Duke of B
edford class, those sort of people, or to do with landed gentry. Largely speaking, landed gentry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How did people think about the police in those days, were they their enemies or their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I don't think they were averse to the police. I know there are certain characters - famous characters in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose} like there were in other districts too that - were prominent - wrongdoers, but generally - generally speaking - the police were - reasonably tolerant - crowd of people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Were you threatened with the police if you did anything naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 It's rather queer because the drunken}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 ess that I used to see the police didn't seem to be - in my child's mind I don't remember the police interfering very much in the drunken}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 ess. N}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 . They would more today. Of course, yes, they would, but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Your home was rented wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you ever see the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No, I don't think we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did he have a collector?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 You see, oftentimes - the landlord'd own - well many houses. Very ver
y few people owned their own houses in those days, they couldn't earn - they couldn't earn enough money, although I grant you - but I know the average - the average house of workers house wouldn't cost more than about two hundred pounds, two fifty and so 
on. About two fifty pounds wanted a lot of accumulating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 But you don't remember ever seeing your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How was the rent paid then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh there was a rent caller. Yes, of course, there was a rent - the rent man called. Ah yes, that
 would be the landlord, of course, yes. Agents - now agents - I worked for an agent - oh yes, I worked for an agent when I was - thirteen for a short time, about - six months. And I used to collect rents. There were agents, yes. But - they were auctioneer
s queer enough, auctioneers - and estate and agents, auction - auction - auctioneers, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 And they would also collect the rent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Yes. But of course you see - in the - in those days there was - perhaps you wouldn't - I - I put the cu
ps out mum, there's the tea strainer and - just outside too. There was in those days a lot of what we - what - what was known as - moonlight flitting, did you ever hear that. That's right, yes. Well it was rather queer because I had a cousin - I had a cou
s
in - well an uncle, he was a - he was a jewel - he was a - a gold chaser lived in - did I tell you about this, perhaps I didn't - well living in Finsbury Park and - he was a - a very skilled - chaser, gold chaser, silver chaser, had - that was - that - th
a
t was - quite a skilled trade in those days, he worked for a jewellery in London. Then there was a German - there was a German method came in and and completely wiped it out, like that, and he was - he was sacked of course. And - they got so much in debt,
 he couldn't find a job - and eventually - we managed somehow to in - to get him to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Luton{\*\xmlclose}
. His - his furniture. Otherwise you see those days it was - sold up, sold up was quite a - quite a - a - a well known term, people were sold up you see, if the rent go
t in arrears too much they were turn out of the house, the - the furniture was just put on the - in the roadway on the path, and it was sold by the landlord to any - any -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What happened to the family then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Well they had to do the best they could. Get anywhere they could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Did you tell me if you ever had any help from the parish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
Yes. My mother - my - when - when my father - when my father died - she was left with four children under the age of eleven, I told you, she had Parish Relief - by the Board - Board of Guardians granted }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008  ei}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008 gh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 teen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence a week and two loaves. That's right, eighteen pence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 How did you feel, did she resent that at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 She gave it up after a few weeks time because she'd got to go to the Board of 
Guardians to collect it, and she resented it. So she - she used to - work in the that trade and - and sew hats you see, and keep us going that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 She'd rather do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 Oh yes. But when - funnily enough, when - when - when my brother died those
 few years afterwards, about five or six years afterwards when my brother eventually died - the Board of Guardians somehow got the news of the family died from heart disease, apart from one who was - a boy of - thirteen, and - they paid my fee to - five s
h
illings each week to go to Brompton Hospital. Yes. I used to get the five shillings and the firm that I worked for allowed me to go - go to Brompton, and so I used to go to Brompton - I'd got to get to the hospital about - quarter past nine in the morning
, which meant catch - catching the train from Luton, catching a horse bus from - St Pancras to Brompton hospital which cost me four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence, and I used to have to sit on the top deck, I think I got a - a little cheaper - rate, it was open you see, with just -
 leather covers to cover over the knees in case of rain - if it rained well it rained you see, and then - from Brompton hospital I used to save the four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence coming back to - St Pancras, would walk - to City Road - City Road where - where I used to get a - a three course meal for five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
pence. Now the - that was Alexandra Trust it was called, it was a - a new sort of - serve yourself - a self service restaurant, and she opened it, the - Alexandra, and - used to get this - three course meal for five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 pence. So I saved the four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid415648\charrsid3227008  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 
pence which - with another penny got my midday meal. I went -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 It took you a whole day I expect to do that didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9069422 GL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 I used to get home about five o'clock, you see, we used to sit in the - in the hospital - at Brompton Hospita
l was nearly all tuberculosis, well I - did I tell you about the forms - used to - Brompton Hospital was just like a prison. Used to have a long room for out patients, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}
Brompton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Hospital{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was a TB hospital in those days, and - they simply had forms, no backs to them. And it used to be crowded - people used to get there, the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 people used to get there quite early. I used to - I used to get there before nine o'clock of course, that meant - it used to take about three quarters of an hour to get from - St Pa
ncras to Brompton Hospital. And then they used to sit on these forms for about two hours until me turn came for the doctor, but you could get a penny bowl of soup which was - brought in from a - in-patients hospital. And it was a - it was - it was the mos
t
 - ter - it was a terrible experience because these people - these people were coughing - in the - in the various - serious stages of tuberculosis, you can understand can't you, I remember teaming up with a little girl who was a little bit younger than my
self, she was a TB - patient, I wasn't you see, I was heart disease, and - or at least supposed to be. And - she somehow she - didn't come anymore after a time or two, I suppose she'd just died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1203760 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8460570\charrsid3227008 What treatment did they give you for your heart disease?
